==English==
===Etymology===
Latin ''[[nil#Latin|nīl]]'' ‘nothing’, ''[[desperandum|dēspērandum]]'', gerund of ''[[desperare|dēspērāre]]'' ‘despair’, as used in ''Nil desperandum Teucro duce at auspice Teucro'' ‘no need to despair with Teucer as your leader and Teucer to protect you’, in [[w:Horace|Horace]], ''Odes''.

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/nɪl dɛspəˈrændəm/}}

===Interjection===
'''nil desperandum'''

# Do not despair.

----

==Latin==
===Idiom===

# nothing to be despaired of 
#:''Nil desperandum Teucro duce et auspice Teucro'' (there is nothing to despair about with Teucer as our leader and Teucer as our protector). &mdash; [[Horace]], Odes, I.vii.27 (translation Benham's Book of Quotations).
# never despair.
#I am not going to give up.  Not for giving up, as in: this is not for giving up on.